For more information on scifi-RNA-seq, please read the Nature Methods article (https://t.co/M75QjxoMF7). To establish the method in your lab, we prepared a detailed website and protocol: https://t.co/tz9sn4bj8E. 13/13

Using the thermoligation trick, scifi single-cell sequencing can be extended to other modalities and multi-omics readouts. The concept can also be implemented on open microfluidics platforms and sub-nanoliter well plates. Lots of scope for creativity and new assays. 12/13

scifi-RNA-seq will be most useful for three applications: (1) cell atlas projects of complex tissues, organs, organisms; (2) profiling of large sample collections and patient cohorts; and (3) perturbation studies at the single-cell level, including drug and CRISPR screens. 11/13

We benchmarked scifi-RNA-seq against 10x Genomics scRNA-seq, and multi-round combinatorial indexing in microwell plates. Our method showed superior data quality compared to combinatorial indexing, and greatly improved throughput and multiplexing compared to 10x Genomics. 10/13 https://t.co/zlZ7ZJNMdu

Massive multiplexing: An extra feature of scifi-RNA-seq is the use of round1 barcodes to label experimental conditions, combining thousands of samples without special reagents. We used this for an arrayed CRISPR screen with single-cell readout of T cell receptor activation. 9/13 https://t.co/8MQziPxT9R

Large-scale profiling: On the 10x Genomics system, scifi-RNA-seq easily produces ~150k single-cell transcriptomes from a single channel, or >1.2 million for a full chip. We tested this with a mixture of four human cell lines, resulting in high-quality profiles. 8/13 https://t.co/h60Zm53KAU

Inside the microfluidic droplets, we add a round2 barcode by ligation with a thermostable ligase. While round1 barcodes are shared by all cells in the same plate well, and round2 barcodes are shared by all cells in the same droplet, the combination identifies single cells. 7/13 https://t.co/kL8nRrL9N6

To utilize overloaded droplets for single-cell analysis, scifi-RNA-seq uses one round of whole-transcriptome pre-indexing on a 384 well-plate. This way, cDNA is labelled with round1 barcodes before overloading the microfluidic device with multiple cells per droplet. 6/13 https://t.co/abB5mNMCWI

We discovered that microfluidic droplet generators tolerate massive overloading, and we found a way to use this for ultra-high-throughput scRNA-seq. On the 10x Genomics system, we could load 1.5M nuclei per channel ‚Äì ~10 cells per droplet & 100 times the recommended amount. 5/13 https://t.co/1PnNMst8ef

To minimize doublet formation, cells are usually loaded at very low concentration. This workaround leaves most droplets without a cell, even though they contain all the expensive reagents needed to generate a sequencing library. Can we be more efficient than that? 4/13

Microfluidic droplet generators are very popular for single-cell sequencing, but they suffer from a major conceptual limitation: Cell doublets (i.e., two cells loaded into the same emulsion droplet) receive the same cell barcode and create confounded profiles. 3/13 https://t.co/01er3C8nWj

The development of scifi-RNA-seq was led by @PaulDatlinger, who guides us through the paper in today‚Äôs tweetorial. Data analysis by @afrendeiro. Great team effort by @BockLab and the Biomedical Sequencing Facility at @CeMM_News. 2/13

The Five Dysfunctions of a Team: A Leadership FableThe book reveals the five dysfunctions of why teams even the best ones-often struggle.It outlines a powerful model and actionable steps that can be used to overcome these common hurdles and build a cohesive, effective team. https://t.co/jpmStDL05M
Inattention to ResultsIf the team members don‚Äôt feel accountable, they put their own needs [ego, recognition, career development etc.] ahead of the team goals. The result is that the team loses.
Avoidance of AccountabilityLack of commitment results in team members not making each other accountable. If one has not bought into the decision, they won‚Äôt make their peers too accountable.

Lack of CommitmentFear of conflict results in lack of commitment. As team members have not bought into the decisions, they don‚Äôt feel committed to the same which resulting in an environment where ambiguity prevails.

Fear of ConflictLack of trust results in fear of conflict which in turn results in team members incapable of engaging in debates or openly voicing their opinions. The team completely avoids conflicts which results in inferior results.

Absence of TrustIt takes trust for team members to stand up for their weaknesses and to take responsibility for mistakes. How else would you ask for help if you pretend to be perfect?If the trust is there, you win as a team!

On Thursday we analysed our final sequencing run. This has taken an enormous effort by large teams of highly skilled individuals. We are continuing providing SARS-CoV-2 support to research studies & countries around the world. I'm immensely proud of everyone who made this happen

There were no breaks for Christmas, New Years,.... Many late nights & weekends were worked, and countless emergencies were responded to. We undertook over 150 bespoke analyses of genomic data, getting synthesised data back so that action could be taken where needed.

For the past 15 months the team at @thequadram have been rapidly sequencing SARS-CoV-2 samples from hospitals in Norfolk, Suffolk and Essex, without fail, providing detailed genomic epidemiological analysis straight back to local clinicians within a few hours.

DeepNull uses the set of traits for individuals in a sample, and their linear covariates, to learn a model which minimizes the error in predicting that trait from the covariates. 10\ I say no to FOMO. I only join meetings where I add value and/or should be involved to support a team or help make a decision. This is the hardest one for me. I love being a part of everything, but it‚Äôs not practical.

Every time you look at a subway railing, know that it contains both the map of the antibiotic resistance and a possible source of NEW antibiotics, plus phages and CRISPR arrays that could be used in diagnostics or therapeutics, just like a rainforest under your fingers üåøüëà /19

Finally, @cemmeydan and @dcdanko built an interactive map for the species across the world's cities and their metadata, plus annotation from The Microbe Directory led by @asierra93 @krista_ryon  https://t.co/AO7sHbkfQa. Here is the link: https://t.co/Xo4nxXNOfD  /18 https://t.co/Sck0gUEsiq

The air also carries a rich source of new BGCs, including proteins associated with the synthesis of terpenes, bacteriocins, polyketides (polyketide synthases), and those that encode non-ribosomal peptide synthetases (NRPSs) and NRPS-like proteins /17 https://t.co/rc2yrr2vux

The source of the DNA was different in each city, with most being from the "core urban" microbiome of 31 species, human skin, and soil, but occasionally some evidence of animal or human feces, or wastewater; make sure you wash your hands! /16 https://t.co/oCQbl1rCOk

Each city's air also had a unique microbial profile, with two skin commensals (C. acnes and M. luteus) making up nearly 50% of the public transit air microbiome species across the six tested cities, all with their own genetic variants and thus their own unique clades /15 https://t.co/PixtRNCbZ8

Then Marius Dybwad and Patrick Lee lead the matching collections of the air microbiome from some of the same cities at the same time, which also mapped microbes and AMR genes around the world: https://t.co/a81voonXMO /14

We also used the MAGs to find >4.2 million new peptides (all at least 500 amino acids long) that represent novel biosynthetic gene clusters (BGCs), which we are now following up on with @donia_lab and Arbor Bio. Tokyo had the greatest bang for the buck in terms of new BGCs /13 https://t.co/pSmFip1n1I

then, with @omarabudayyeh and @jgooten, we mined the metagenome-assembled genomes (MAGs) to find >800K new CRISPR arrays, which showed the ongoing dynamics of bacteria battling their ever-evolving viruses and some unknown CRISPR types /12 https://t.co/6DkLeHOaY9

To browse all these AMR genes across the world, we worked with @johnbrownstein and his team, who overlaid our AMR genes data with his resistance map, which you can see here https://t.co/nuPmBuTDTQ /11 https://t.co/ISV42h3YKy

There is some evidence that the proportion of AMR genes in a given city are actually a mirror of the reported usage of antibiotics for the population, based on W.H.O. data, across plasmid and chromosome-derived sequences: /10 https://t.co/wxRPyE9es2

We also found that genes for antimicrobial resistance (AMR) were evident across many surfaces, also in a city-specific fashion, but that these AMR genes were at levels below what one might find in a gut microbiome or soil sample, which is good news for straphangers /9 https://t.co/puWllGriq2

This has broad implications for a person's "reasonable expectation of privacy" and GINA laws, since you carry signatures that are beyond just your human DNA and which can be combined with other forensics data, as @EranElhaik and I have recently shown /8 https://t.co/1N2TZvRkfU https://t.co/EgfjKiG4mG

There are distinct microbial signatures for each of the world's cities, which enable almost 90% accuracy to predict where you are from, based on your metagenome; this gets better and better with more samples and will only improve in the future as sequencing continues /7 https://t.co/zRKusIPtI0

We can use these indices to compare not only of all DNA found on Earth, but someday also compare this to DNA/RNA that might be found on Mars or other planets; our metagenomics framework has already been used as a pilot framework for planetary protection https://t.co/WmRlNIl6G3 /6

‚ö†Ô∏èA caveat with MSig markers ‚Äì equally as CNA markers or driver mutation #markers ‚Äì is that these features #correlate with each other in cell line panels, and also correlate with gene expression/subtypes. Thus drug associations are often indirect & may not reflect causal links.

Additionally, we identify e.g. interactions between a #BER-deficiency-associated MSig, and AXL and/or KIT inhibition; and also identify a mutational signature ("CL5") that associates with sensitivity to topoisomerase-II inhibition. https://t.co/Q9bA4F5CRr

Even though HDACi drugs often inhibit many different #HDAC proteins, a joint analysis with CRISPR data prioritized HDAC1 and HDAC3 as targets in MMR-deficient cellsSpeculatively, a #microsatellite repeat in HDAC2 may generate LoF indel mutations, increasing reliance on paralogs https://t.co/AYH84W5fHe

~800 associations were found that replicated >=3 times (i.e. were seen in different tissues and/or using different 'two-way' replication methods), suggesting a higher priority for follow-up. ü•ºüß™One example are some signatures of MMR failure and sensitivity to #epigenetic drugs

Robust associations with MSig obtained thus were similarly or more numerous as those involving driver mutations, CNA, or DNA methylation.  An example of an expected MSig association was between the #APOBEC MSigs and sensitivity to several ATR inhibitors. https://t.co/FnxNauFstQ

This 'two-way' randomization test works not only with MutSig but also with classical drug sensitivity markers such as driver mutations (see BRAF example).  New candidate associations were recovered, e.g. #ARID1A mutations were associated with AKTi and with #AKT2 k.o. by CRISPR. https://t.co/1It18q5Vj9

Next we asked if individual MSigs associate with response to particular drugs. To prioritize robust links, we introduced a method to test for drug associations that #replicate in independent data: CRISPR screens (P.Score), or PRISM drug screening, or across 2 drugs w/same target https://t.co/6NFu3NX11K

(side note: global gene expression profiles were highly predictive of drug response, perhaps because they reflect cancer subtypes. However MSigs were complementary -- they could predict response profiles of additional drugs when combined w/ expression, and also w/ other markers) https://t.co/nU6Rik2dBW

We compared cancer cell line MSigs in their ability to predict response profilesüìäin a drug screen (GDSCüíä) using Random Forests. In most cancers, MSigs outpeformed the copy number alterations, mutations in driver genes, and DNA methylation in predicting drug sensitivity. https://t.co/36KD2kiggw

Mutational signatures (#MSigs) ‚Äì extracted using NMF similar to other mut. sig. work ‚Äì were matched to the known SBS signatures from Cosmic, recovering 50 SBS at FDR ~2% (of that 29 at a more stringent treshold). Our signatures also have an #indel component. https://t.co/Aft13FCtGb

We propose an "#ancestry-matching" approach. Here each cell line is matched to a similar-ancestry normal sample from TCGA. This improves reconstruction of #somatic trinucleotide profiles, likely by accounting for ancestry-specific #germline mutational processes. https://t.co/V0pcP4dYDc

We analyzed mutational signatures in ~1,000 #cancer cell lines. A challenge here is that germline variation is difficult to remove from cell line #genomes. This is because a matched-healthy tissue from same donor is usually not available.

Takeaways from this study:- Minimize the possibility of introducing unwanted variations (limit batches) & use consistent storage conditions and equipment.- Corrective measures can still be performed in silico, we suggest RUV-III-NB as a consistent and robust method.

We also benchmarked and compared the performance of RUV-III-NB against other popular batch correction tools, including ComBat, ComBat-seq, RUVg, and RUVs. We found that RUV-III-NB was the most consistently robust across our sensitivity & specificity metrics. https://t.co/qyeRVgYUV1

Among others, we identified experimental factors such as storage conditions and freeze-thaw cycles as major likely sources of unwanted variations in microbiome data. We also observed that these variations mostly affect highly abundant taxa, such as Bacteroidia and Bacilli. https://t.co/VZzGrP7OyV

To analyze the effects, we used RUV-III-NB, a novel computational method utilizing a Negative Binomial-based glm with log link function to model the effect of unwanted variations on the sequencing count at taxon-level, and correct them.https://t.co/OKopmWOJNW

In our study, to assess the effect of unwanted technical variations, we used a controlled dataset of faecal samples from pigs, encompassing up to 21 combinations of deliberately introduced technical variations, and we then assessed their effect on microbiome composition. https://t.co/Hs4uNWeFhS

Unwanted technical variations are virtually unavoidable in any scientific experiment, and that of course includes microbiome data. Left unaddressed, it may affect the observed abundance of various microbes in relation to others, and importantly conclusions, which is problematic. https://t.co/LUQPnnqs2w

Happy to announce that our preprint (my first one üòÅ) is finally out!We assessed how unwanted technical variations affect microbiome data, and suggest a novel computational batch correction tool, RUV-III-NB.@phylogeo @minouye271 @SJPamp & Agus Salimhttps://t.co/OgqbNInMOc https://t.co/14eF1s5IlO

Which also means it's transformation invariant as well. üòâAlthough those transformations can affect how missing values might go against you if you didn't use this (or tried the trick of just replacing stuff on your own).

We've used previous versions of this code extensively, and it seems to work very, very well for looking at correlation. The Kendall-tau makes almost no assumptions about "how" your data is correlated, using discordant and concordant pair comparisons,
I spent the last week converting {SciPy} very nice implementation to {Rcpp}, and then split this off into it's very ownüì¶ with only the {Rcpp} dependency (and {furrr} if you want multiprocessing).
At the same time, we were also adding the p-value test to the code, and "learned" about the *fast* way of calculating these correlations, that would take us from O(n^2) to O(nlogn).

And then in working up manuscript results, realized you could just use normal Kendall-tau and replace missing values with something smaller than the smallest value, and you would get the same answer (we actually tested our code this way once we figured it out).

We recently (last fall) thought of a nicer way to incorporate missingness into the Kendall-tau correlation measure.We spent a lot of time thinking about it, and came up with lots of crazy special calculations for it,
We've previously tried to include it into Pearson correlation, you can see those efforts in our other üì¶codehttps://t.co/3UwjB5l851

Motivation: -omics data frequently has a lot of missing values. Most of those missing values are "not-missing-at-random", but due to analytical instrument sensitivities.Therefore, missingness should convey *some information* and contribute to correlation.

6/ Thus, we believe there are variants within this region that influence responses to acute lung injury in rodents. It's bittersweet to move on to my postdoc and pass this project on to others, but I'm so excited to see what comes from it!

5/ Excitingly, this genomic region has been implicated in other lung injury models (hypoxia and SARS-CoV). Additionally, a recent abstract was published suggesting that the syntenic region in humans modifies the relationship between another oxidant pollutant (NO2) and emphysema.

4/ We used a variety of approaches to delimit the QTL and nominate candidate genes, landing on three: Angpt1, Rspo2, and Oxr1. Further validation of these genes in our model is forthcoming, but each has a confirmed role in wound healing, barrier integrity, or oxidative stress.

3/ In this preprint, we focus on total protein in the lungs which is a nonspecific marker of lung injury. We see that this response is heritable, and identified a significant locus on mouse Chr. 15 associated with its variation across the strains.
2/ We exposed a cohort of 55 Collaborative Cross strains to filtered air or ozone (in sex-/age-matched pairs) to identify loci associated with ozone-induced respiratory responses.

l for one, look forward to the moment when there will be so many variants, characterised by such long series of numbers, that hardly anyone will be able to keep track of them, and even fewer, besides the scientists in charge of their surveillance, give a toss about them.12/

Regularly updated vaccines and boosters may be required at least for the more vulnerable in society to minimise the burden. Though, given the extraordinary surveillance in place and our ability to update vaccines promptly, this should be manageable.11/

This cost of such a transition to an endemic dynamic for #SARSCoV2 should be lessened by the availability of effective vaccines. Thankfully #SARSCoV2 is also fairly benign for young children with ensures the first exposure in life would cause limited morbidity/mortality.10/

Such regular emergence of #SARSCoV2 lineages escaping host neutralisation provided by vaccination or prior infection would be largely comparable to what is observed for seasonal influenza or the 229E endemic coronavirus.9/https://t.co/SJKvOAFhU9

Eventually, there will likely be emergence of 'immune escape' lineages that can readily reinfect hosts who have been previously infected or vaccinated. Though, the hosts should still benefit from their cellular immunity reducing symptom severity.8/

We can't make any robust prediction about future intrinsic #SARSCoV2 virulence. This being said, morbidity/mortality is expected to decrease drastically as the host population acquires immunisation (through prior infection and vaccination).7/https://t.co/8BR26BSQUk

Viruses will always be selected to be more transmissible. That's evolution - the fact that any replicating entity common today had ancestors that were likely good at replicating. Thus #SARSCoV2 transmissibility is most unlikely to go down. in the future.6/

With increasing population immunisation globally, the selective pressures on the virus may become even stronger and more homogeneous, and we may observe further convergent evolution, to the point that the number of 'variants' will likely become difficult to keep track of.5/

Though interestingly, mutations and deletions that are common in VoCs/VoIs have emerged multiple times independently in hundreds of different viral genetic backgrounds without those lineages necessarily being particularly successful.4/https://t.co/5KXr1WFCqW https://t.co/jGkCFt8Ir6

These second two "reasons for doing genetics" are actually the ones we can get to work *now* and are arguably far more important than prediction (again, reminding ourselves that prediction is prediction in a context; a context which varies but that is assumed to be random).

Furthermore, because we all have a common genome, we don't need to co-measure these genetic effects on the same individuals - indeed, it is *better* to measure one genetic effect for one thing (eg, heart function) on one cohort and another on another cohort (eg, heart disease)

we can be most confident of that randomisation inside families - which chromosome you inherited from your grandparents via your parents is a random choice (it is sort of amazing how random it is) but we can also often convince ourselves of randomisation between in people.
In this framework one use the fact not that genetics is that *predictive* but rather that genetics is a perturbation and often one assigned at random.

Why is MLOps important?When the data changes, the machine learning models need to be readjusted and regularly deployed- Continuous deployment (CD)
Why is MLOps important?If your machine learning model is embedded in a complete project, it is probably not alone, we have an orchestra that plays and needs to be managed- Continuous integration (CI)
Why is MLOps important?Just because your model is hitting now doesn't mean it will be doing so 6 months from nowModel drift is real!- Continuous training (CT)

The full MLOps life cycle- Data Engineering: Get and clean the data recurring if necessary- Model Engineering: Model training, evaluation, testing, and packaging- Model Deployment: integrating the trained model. Model serving, performance monitoring

Did you think bringing your machine learning model to production was the hard part?What about model drift?Now MLOps comes into play but how does it work and what are good tools?What is:- Continuous integration (CI)- Continuous deployment (CD)- Continuous training (CT) https://t.co/ACjeIiLOEx

@JettenMijke @celia_vgelder As a pilot @DTL_nl & ELIXIR added content was to the @emblebi Competency Hubtool, for 3 data steward roles (policy, research and infrastructure) and eight competence areas: https://t.co/XgAtdwFSUt(2/n)

All said, @nanopore reads really provide more content, and this gives us confidence to do the entire panel via this technology - with the improvements in prep and quality it will be even better - and we get methylation status in the tissue used for genomic samples in addition.

Because we get multiple ONT reads in each sample, each with its own methylation read out we can get fine grained views of the methylation status - here is one example of differentially methylated CpG islands. https://t.co/32JZR4s09C

(A note; this might be "within cell" haplotype specific methylation where there are some genetic effects directly impacting methylation, often locally and in cis. Or it might be, say, developmental changes that shifts the proportion of cell types in the brain samples).

We only have 12 samples, so we can't assess any methylation/genetics loci, but by using the sib-pair structure of part of the MIKK panel we can see sib-lines clustering together, showing a substantial contribution of genetics to methylation. https://t.co/cyYCZxcJ7p

Nanopore reads are not just long, they also read out cytosine methylation (as well as other modifications, but cytosine methylation is the most robust). This allows the same dataset to show DNA methylation in the sample (brain here). There is plenty of CpG methylation in Medaka https://t.co/46ugqDBTdP

When the graph deletes from the annotated reference (HdrR) we can have the very clear idea about what gene content is removed. Here is an example involving Cytochrome P450 genes. https://t.co/GLzqwpswJ4

One question is whether these graph segments have any 'content' - they clearly do. Here is an example where the two paths in the graph have very different alignments to RNAseq. https://t.co/xvFCAYFOfq
These graphs are *great* but using the graph is a bit mind-bending, and all credit to @AdrienLeger2, @IanBrettell and @tomaswfitz  for getting their heads around the graph and get results out.

Some of this might be noise (or "chaff" in the assembly parlance) but it is clear much is not, because two or more independent MIKK assemblies contributed to the same part of the graph, as well as MIKK to HNI or HSOK. https://t.co/MIjhgkDvJL

To explore this dataset better we use @lh3lh3's excellent minigraph with the "classic" laboratory inbred lines of HdrR, HNI (a Northern Medaka line) and HSOK from Korea and then the 12 MIKK panel lines. The resulting graph was nearly twice as big as the HdrR linear reference. https://t.co/tkT7rGdom9

These data assembled very well with N50s (N50 is the weighted median contig length; assembly metric) 500KB - 900KB, longest contigs above 5MB (!). When aligned to the excellent HdrR reference we get alignment N50s of alignments at a pretty consistent 200KB of alignment

We did 12 samples 4-way multiplexed on PromethION flow cells (actually quite some time ago - looking forward to doing on new chemistry). We did a pretty standard prep, giving us read lengths N50s of ~7KB (which is actually quite low to what one can get on more modern preps).

(Noted in this paper, and *yawn* noted again here is my COI: I am a long established paid consultant to Oxford Nanopore; my postdoc at the time who did much of this work, @AdrienLeger2 got some free flow cells - in fact for other things - and now works @nanopore).

In our second paper on the MIKK panel we sequenced using @nanopore 12 lines to see the impact of this long read technology has on understanding genetic variation - the answer is quite a bit. https://t.co/lUY0UvQ5dl

Overall we've create this inbred panel, MIKK, for medaka fish, the first inbred panel from the wild in vertebrates. We are, as I type, doing the complex "vary genetics and vary environment in a controlled way" across the panel. We encourage the community to explore this with us!

Finally we performed a proof of principle RNAseq experiment across the panel. This worked (as expected) - with enrichment of eQTLs across the gene (similar plots and power to the early human eQTL studies). https://t.co/LSDXOLOUrX
This is consistent with the Northern Medaka fish being a separate species which rarely mates in the wild with southern Medaka fish (though these do mate in the lab).

We also confirmed a previous observation that *despite* a closer divergence time between "Southern" (MIKK included) and "Northern" Medaka fish, the MIKK panel shows more introgression with the Korean medaka population. https://t.co/eBOUfMGnmi

Medaka chromosome 2 is interesting here; far tighter LD which is completely consistent with its large genetic mapping distance per MB; chr2 has a different repeat content to other Medaka fish chromosomes.

Medaka fish populations is "deeper" than human populations - more individuals over a longer period of time, giving shorter blocks of LD. We previously reported this in the wild medaka paper, and recapitulate it here. https://t.co/TF6LLFLYHq
However, we have plenty of LoFs in interesting genes, including ~1,400 of genes orthologous to disease causing genes in humans; again, a potential immediate resource of interest.

When we look at Loss of Function mutations in protein coding genes in Medaka fish we do see them, but they are more likely to be hetreozygous (no surprise) and when they are homozygous they are less likely to be in orthologous dosage sensitive genes in humans.

Without the registration and an ID number, difficult/slow/impossible hacks are needed to get a phone, a bank account, purchase accounts at work (!), apps for e.g. deliveries, drs appointments, our door bell (!)... Dysfunctional @Skatteverket has put us in a limbo for months.

Moving to a new country is always a hassle, but getting set up in Sweden is proving to be way worse than the US or Switzerland due to a single point of failure: EVERYTHING relies on being in the population registry, but this takes up to 6 months due to delays at @Skatteverket.

The importance of genotype-independent forces in this system suggests that therapeutic interventions involving pore-dwelling species might focus on removing resident populations over optimizing probiotic fitness.

This anatomy-induced population fragmentation reduces competition between genotypes and thereby promotes strain coexistence. Moreover, the priority effect inside pores may explain why strains are stable over time, despite the skin‚Äôs exposure to the environment. https://t.co/288zKwIpRO

We propose that pore anatomy and physiology create these bottlenecks by making it rare for a would-be colonizer to descend into the pore. A lucky cell that reaches the depths of the pore can rapidly expand and block new migrants. https://t.co/9mtfc0jSaF

This striking pattern could arise from adaptive sweeps. But, an absence of adaptive signatures suggests that selective sweeps can‚Äôt explain low intrapore diversity.We therefore explored the possibility that neutral population bottlenecking might be responsible. https://t.co/4jDDxDJZGs

Why could this be? Phylogenetic trees provide a clue. Colonies from a pore aren‚Äôt just simply from the same lineage - they also share nearly identical genomes (typically <1 SNV apart)!For example, here‚Äôs part of a phylogeny from Subject 1 (pores with > 1 colony highlighted). https://t.co/jqb5SIfk8W
Yet, each pore is dominated by just a single lineage!For instance, three pores within a 1 cm patch of skin each harbored a different lineage. https://t.co/TwPy2FscFO

We don‚Äôt find any evidence of niche specificity to anatomical regions (neither to forehead/nose/back nor to pores/surface). Instead, all strains appear to be capable of colonizing pores and residing on any sebaceous skin region. https://t.co/3XTLC7xKx8

We clustered colonies into lineages (< 35 SNVs genome-wide). The number of lineages on a person provides a lower bound for the number of independent colonizations. A typical person has multiple lineages, including some from the same strain type. Subject 1 highlighted on left: https://t.co/9JGKNcnkLU

A combination of high spatial resolution (sampling single skin pores) and high genetic resolution (down to a single mutation across the genome, powered by colony-sequencing) enabled us to reconstruct evolution and migration of C. acnes on individual people. https://t.co/En6RFsthzd

As I have said before, both for humane reasons of wanting to minimise suffering and narrow, selfish reasons of wanting to reduce new variants and have a growing world economy... we need to vaccinate a large proportion of the world. Nothing else matters than this in 2021.

In the big picture though the concern in the UK over B.1.617.2, or the worries about the Terraces reopening in France is small beer compared to the serious risks in the rest of the world with faster transmitting variants from 2020 and lower vaccination levels.

As such countries will need to titrate their NPIs (non pharmaceutical interventions) with their TTI with their vaccination levels. It is a complex world to navigate this summer. I sort of wish more countries would just ... wait for vaccination, but I get that there are drivers.

However, opening up with less vaccinated individuals does have more risks - risks of hospitalisations (less deaths as most countries have vaccinated the most at risk first) and long COVID. These are ... things to be concerned about.

Outside of UK across Europe, the steady and effective vaccine roll out has occurred. Broadly most European countries are planning to relax in some way earlier than the UK roadmap (I think with some justification as they can learn from Israel and UK). Vaccine supply is now strong.
How this resolves I am not sure - we simply need more data - it's that straightforward and speculation is just that. Plan for the worst, hope for the best is a reasonable mindset.

The growing transmissibility of #SARSCoV2 will likely stretch local elimination strategies to their limit. I find it difficult to imagine that #SARSCoV2 might not become endemic globally over the coming years.5/

VoCs are not homogenous nor immutable as they continue to evolve by accumulating mutations, like all other #SARSCoV2 lineages (at a rate of ~2 mutations/month). Other VoCs will appear, likely intrinsically more transmissible and able to evade, at least in part, immunisation.4/

Some combinations of mutations/deletions have been particularly successful, leading to those linages being referred to as Variants of Concern (VoCs) or Variants of Interest (VoIs). Examples of questions you can add to your tracker:- achieve my vision for my love relationship?- achieve my vision for my financial life?- preserve all client relationships?- be grateful for what I have?- avoid angry or destructive comments about others?

I recommend starting all questions with "Did I do my best to..."Core questions may include, Did I do my best to...- set clear goals?- make progress toward goal achievement?- find meaning?- be happy?- build positive relationships?- be fully engaged?

So you're questions in the tracker will allow you to:- Create more of what you want- Preserve what you want to keep- Eliminate that which you don't want- Accept the negative elements

The foundation of microbiology has always been the cultivation of before-then hard-to-cultivate microbes. I have huge admiration for all successful cultivations of CPR and DPANN. Many approaches and each is a unique contribution. It's hard and in some cases underappreciated work.

Lots of method development is still needed, especially in  how to best separate epibionts from both free-living cells and viruses and how to best assay for epibiont growth. Plenty of assumptions could fail. Please perform due diligence on all suggested methods before attempting.

I challenge you to think of a reason why a scaled up version of this untargeted approach would not yield more epibiont species. Try 100 different potential hosts, find 2.. 5.. 20 epibionts? This would be boon for the study of these enigmatic organisms.

I explain my rationale for sharing now. Basically, Batinovic et. al showed cultivation of epibiont by adding <0.2-um filtrate to a pure culture of a potential host - untargeted, without knowing the host was a host or the epibionts were even present üí™https://t.co/xwI1Y8svdB

Because of balance of maximising study power, cohorts like @GLADStudy and @DepressionAu that samples people who have experienced depression at more than the population prevalence will be central to the next wave of depression genetics.

However, studies are now getting so large that they are held back a bit by the preponderance of controls (given a fixed total sample size, it's more effective to have equal numbers of cases and controls).
The relatively high prevalence of experiences of depression has made such large sample sizes feasible, as data can feasibly be collected from community, population health, and consumer cohorts.
Levinson et al predicted "we expect to detect multiple MDD associations when ùëõ exceeds 75,000 to 100,000 cases", which has more than come to pass.

Finally, previous research has shown that viral phosphodiesterases (PDEs) can antagonise OAS antiviral activity. We used a custom PDE HMM profile to screen all available Coronaviridae genomes and confirm that no known Rhinolophoidea infecting coronavirus expresses a PDE. https://t.co/yxBoV3SSqx

We then screened the genomes of 44 different bat species to show that this LTR insertion is in fact specific to the bat Rhinolophoidea superfamily (inserted ~ 55mya), while all other bats seem to have a prenylation site. https://t.co/CXENnv0D6g
What we found is an LTR insertion right where the prenylation motif encoding region should have been! disrupting the production of a prenylated OAS1 in this bat species. https://t.co/iktzgeWHQ1

After seeing the lab results that prenylated OAS1 antagonises SARS-CoV-2 in humans we decided to have a look a this gene in horseshoe bats - the likely reservoir host of SARS-CoV-2's proximal ancestor.

This could be another remarkable example of how ancient viruses may have played a role in modern immune responses, in this case interactions in the natural host potentially modulating the outcome in the resulting cross species transmission. 7/n
In this case the modulation does not appear to be via a direct role in becoming incorporated in the immune response, but via knocking out an aspect of a pre-existing response. 6/n

We have been exploring the ability of integrated ancient viruses to modulate contemporary immunity to viral challenge in bats, in this review, as part of endogenous viral element derived immunity. 5/n https://t.co/C5k2sqBPmQ

MER74A is in fact, a member of the ERV-L family of endogenous retroviruses, a group of viruses that have been integrating into the ancestors of mammalian genomes for much of evolutionary history, with varying levels of more recent day activity. 4/n

Even more intriguingly from an evolutionary perspective, 55 million years ago this gene was rendered inactive in horseshoe bats, the likely natural host of SARS-CoV-2, by the insertion of the MER74A 'retrolement'. 3/n

@WilsonLabCVR & co explore the antiviral response of SARS-CoV-2, and show that an immune stimulated gene, OAS1, potently inhibit this coronavirus. Intriguingly, this inhibition appears to vary among humans and could play a role in  pathology. 2/nhttps://t.co/TxZV1kl0ZR

[MINI THREAD] Could an endogenous retrovirus be involved in the ancient evolution of SARS-CoV-2 and have played a role it its interactions with its host? Warning, this is both speculation, and based on a not-yet-peer reviewed preprint. 1/n

Our newly-found peaks and candidate regulatory elements are accessible as a UCSC hub: https://t.co/okgk1iBY1e.  Ultimately, we tested a subset of these elements using a reporter assay and found evidence of promoter and enhancer changes for specific duplicated genes.

To understand mechanisms contributing to the divergence, we dove into ENCODE data but realized that regulatory elements were depleted from our duplications so established a snakemake pipeline to recover ChIP-seq peaks using a published method called CSEM. https://t.co/fpfwCD0QMv https://t.co/mCc6I6QlJ5

This pattern was consistent across even the youngest duplicates, suggesting expression divergence arose at "birth" due to altered regulatory environments and matches previous work by others. In some cases, we found evidence of genes neofunctionalizing (ARHGEF35).

We compared expression levels of 30 human duplicate gene families using matched human/chimp RNA-seq data from diverse tissues and cells and found signatures largely consistent with pseudogenization or neofunctionalization, with derived paralogs often showing lower expression. https://t.co/UXfVy06xC1

And using an irreducible complexity like argument to minimize mutation as a possible mechanism here is just unsound.  Certainly, this does not in any way prove the "natural" origin theories but mutation needs to be considered and not thrown out for the wrong readsons 9/n

Again, I am not saying which theory on COVID19 origins is right or wrong here. But the logic presented in the Wade article that somehow one has to resort to either recombination or purposeful insertion is unsound. Mutation alone could easily have done this. 8/n

It is simply ridiculous to argue that mutation could not have created a small run of specific amino acids in a protein when at the same time we agree that mutation could have created things like the ribosome and such. 7/n

This argument presented in this article (and elsewhere) sounds remarkably close to a commonly used argument by Intelligent Design proponents generally known as "Irreducible Complexity" (e.g. see https://t.co/4I4TmPhxy8) 6/n

The argument relates to the furin cleavage site observed in SARSCOV2 - and here Wade et al. basically argue that mutation could not have led to the multiple changes required to make this furin cleavage site & thus must be the result of recombination or purposeful manipulation 5/n https://t.co/oCmMpxwzMo
However, I have one deep concern about a logical argument presented here (and sometimes elsewhere) that has been used to support the lab origin theories 4/n
And there are a lot of pieces to the story that are still muddled and unclear and need more work 3/n

First, I want to say, as I have said many times before, that I think working on the origins and trying to figure out if it came from a lab in some way or from "nature" is an important research area and I think the answer is still not resolved 2/n

I worked as a jellyfish biologist after my BSc but had a renewed appreciation for all biology. I did a PhD in ecology (lol) using genomics (lol) in marine & freshwater fishes (double lol) & now I work on bird genomics, which I love but never imagined would happen!(4/)

I went into undergrad thinking the only things in the world I wanted to learn about were jellyfish. I didn't like genetics that much (but the labs were cool), I liked ecology but did poorly in my intro eco course, I favoured inverts over verts, marine over freshwater. (3/)

What I find really interesting is that 12 years seem like both a very long time ago, but perhaps not that many years in the big scheme of things. I'd love to know how others have changed in their STEM journies - I'll even go first bc it has been a wild ride (2/)

Fast inference time: FELIX is fully non-autoregressive, avoiding slow inference times caused by an autoregressive decoder.Flexible text editing: FELIX strikes a balance between the complexity of learned edit operations and flexibility in the transformations it models

FELIX uses three techniques to minimize the amount of required data: (1) fine-tuning pre-trained checkpoints, (2) a tagging model that learns a small number of edit operations, and (3) a text insertion task that is very similar to the pre-training task.

Compared to traditional seq2seq methods, FELIX has the following three key advantages:Sample efficiency: Training a high precision text generation model typically requires large amounts of high-quality supervised data.

FELIX, a fast and flexible text-editing system that models large structural changes and achieves a 90x speed-up compared to seq2seq approaches whilst achieving impressive results on four monolingual generation tasks.Abs  https://t.co/pPmLPSABJP https://t.co/rXzqCFtwCn https://t.co/GUeMfS6lLB

There are 2400 known mouse TFs and out of that 41% are expressed in the brain during developmental axon growth.From this subset, 37% TFs are expressed right alongside KLF6 in corticospinal motor neurons, our cell type of interest.

We focused on a pro-growth TF KLF6, and tested the idea that KLF6 + right partners >> KLF6 alone in promoting axon growth following injury. First off, how do you zero in on the right KLF6 partners? This is a non-trivial problem and here's why.

Successful regeneration in the PNS and other species is co-ordinated not by any one TF, but by an interconnected network of 10s of TFs.  Robust CNS regeneration also likely requires groups of interacting TFs for optimal efficacy. We set out to test this hypothesis.

Or if you work in human disease how to go from associations found in cells to therapies. There are many steps between associations and then extracting value from them, and the validation at each step is not along the lines of: push an A/B test to a crowd of willing consumers

Similarly in my field (Comp Bio) we can find lots of associations between different molecular phenotypes across lots of cells in different conditions. What's next? What is the next experiment to do to validate the mechanism? I haven't seen ML solve this.

One place where this argument falls flat I think is in cost of evaluation, or "what's next". E.g. what strings of words are associated with intention, say ... the intent to buy toothpaste. Companies can roll that out and validate their models fairly easily i imagine

For insitutions that already have some form of this, then more needs to be done. Increase funding, assess outcomes and change as neeeded. Some of you know that your programs, which you tout on brochures, are stagnant and are nothign more than window dressing. Do more! 6/n

One remedy, short of overhauling our K-12 system - which needs some serious reimagining (@teachcardona), is for universities to provide targeted preparatory academic training either before matriculation or early in the undergrad or grad experience. 5/n

The biggest factor driving the perpetuation of this lie is that our educational system, from K-12 and beyond, does a seriously inadequate job at preparing students, especially those from marginalized groups, for the rigor of higher education. 4/n

If you're advising or mentoring students, especially marginalized students, irrespective of YOUR training level (K-12, undergrad, grad, post doc, faculty, staff, administrator, etc), please don't perpetuate this lie. This is especially true, if you are a scientist of color.  3/n

This is a lie perpetuated by a system infected with systemic racism. Describing science education in this way is deterimental to addressing the real inequites that exist and is discouraging to too many marginalized students. 2/n

My heart goes out to Indian friends and colleagues. As a scientist I am helping as much as I can but the challenge now is less science more logistics and politics.

In the meantime countries will have to implement NPIs. If there is one thing we've learnt in this pandemic is that it is ... very predictable. This virus *definitely* causes a bad disease often leading to death and *definitely* will grow very quickly if people meet inside.

As well as big picture things (rich countries giving vaccine doses, releasing raw material supplies, providing access to vaccine IP - hats off to Ox/AZ for being well ahead of this in global manufacturing) there is I am sure a host of details.

I presume there is a core group of people focused simply on getting these rates up - in these sorts of systems one always only has one bottleneck in any linear supply chain, and one has to focus on relieving that bottleneck anticipating where the next one will be.

The swirling mix of politics and the importance of getting this right makes this complex waters to navigate, but putting that aside, it is about logistics from raw material supply to places to make the vaccines to delivery to vaccination.

So here I talk more as a citizen; Vaccine manufacturing continues to scale, and we will not regret scaling even further up this year; due to organisations such as @gavi and CEPI we have global structures trusted. We need to get our heads down and use them all.

The challenge is getting the same solution present worldwide - every country, every human at risk. This is now not about science so much; it is about logistics at all different levels and politics, both inside of countries and globally. Definitely outside my expertise.

(Don't take the 45-55% as a well modelled thought through thing - it is a n-of-2 plus some appeal to modelling crude estimation. The diversity of reopening tactics in the summer across EU countries will give I suspect far more information on this).

Crudely it seems somewhere between 45-55% vaccinated is a safe number (both from Israel+UK experience) though there are so many details from previous infections levels through the details of how NPIs and TTIs work; but everyday there is more vaccination the safer citizens are.

Vaccination supply and delivery is now high across the EU, and at some level this is now a mixture of logistics, ensuring vaccination coverage (not trivial in the world of anti-vaxx) and deciding when to release NPIs relative to vaccination rates.

The presence of effective vaccines means that vaccination is a really strong strategy. It has been executed well by Israel and the UK is emerging from lockdown with vaccination replacing NPIs to prevent transmission. US not far behind.

This is on both "old" variants and critically B.1.1.7, the more transmissible variant now dominating much of the north. On the E484K mutation carrying strains it seems very likely vaccines can prevent severe disease (P1 for sure; B.1.351 likely)+ some blunting of transmission

Vaccines have changed the game completely. We have multiple vaccines which are safe (there are some rare adverse events, but very rare) and work. They work at the top end of expectations; they nearly completely prevent severe disease; they significantly reduce transmission.

This latter scenario is close to happening - arguably has happened - in India and it is awful; heartbreaking, wrong and just something to claw back from. Despite the good path US, UK, Israel and the EU are on, this path is a long way off for much of the world.
